comment:
Thank you for contacting the DeKalb County Citizen Help Center. I apologize for the delay in getting back to you. Ramps, Interstate and State Roads and signs referring to the Interstate or State Roads are maintained by Georgia DOT. The area in question is handles by the Atlanta Division of the Georgia DOT in which I am still awaiting a response to my request for an email address in which to forward your concerns.  I’m not sure if a sign will help or if police presence is needed but because the issue happens on the ramp, GADOT will need to be involved. There is a “contact us” section on the  Georgia DOT’s website that you may want to visit:  http://www.dot.state.ga.us/misc/Pages/ContactUs.aspx
 
Sincerely,
 
Cynthdella "Cindy" Thomas
311 Citizen Help Center

comment: This intersection is in desperate need of repair!  People have to cross it slowly because of its bad condition, which then ends up causing major traffic issues.  Perhaps a whole reconstruction is needed to add turning lanes, too.
Another person wants this fixed too!

The City of Atlanta allocates zero money for roads.   The intersection of Fayetteville Road and Flat Shoals Road is not the responsibility of Dekalb County, so the city of Atlanta needs to step and repair and WIDEN the intersection.  The traffic light is so long because there is only one lane in any direction and this is the busiest intersection in the entire area.   The city could have forced new businesses Exxon and the Package store to widen Fayetteville Road at the intersection, but did nothing.   Not only does the road need to be widened but sidewalks away from the road need to be redone.   This entire intersection needs to be improved!

comment:
I think this "improvement" is another example of a knee-jerk reaction to a problem which does more harm than good. Atlanta's roads are being ruined one intersection at a time by these poorly-planned solutions.  Drivers can no longer turn right on red at this intersection in even moderate traffic, since there is no right turn lane any more.  Instead, there is a new curb which serves only to block traffic.

If the goal is to snarl traffic, why not make one lane of North Highland Ave a full-time bike lane, like was done recently to westbound 10th Street?  How about planting a giant Oak tree in the middle of the intersection of Piedmont and Monroe? Why not make the 4 left lanes of the Grady curve a drive-thru car wash?   

The lack of a comprehensive city-wide traffic plan is obvious.
name: atlengdave

comment: A watcher was added to this issue.

I agree that the new curb on N Morningside at N highland is a bad idea for everyone.  I often walk with my kids & drive through that intersection, and the curb does nothing to make the intersection safer for pedestrians.  The pedestrian cross signal needs to be fixed on all sides and it needs to be timed better with the lights.  Perhaps all drivers get a red light when a crossing signal is pressed.  Oh and the bulbs in all of the signals need to be replaced regularly so that people know when to stop and go... really Atlanta DOT... can't keep signals working properly because of bulbs being out?!  That's the most dangerous and most simple thing to keep up on.  

If DOT wants to make more routes safer for kids, one could look at the speeds at which drivers come through the NE (non-calmed) side of N. Morningside Drive.  Erroll Davis, in his infinite wisdom, took away the elementary school busses for this area causing double the driving traffic and double the pedestrians at morning rush hour and school pick up time (although MES has 2 more half-filled busses than last year... hmmm).  The traffic needs have changed since MES orginally was granted the funds to allow DOT to make safer routes to school.  The Morningside community generally feels that the traffic pattern changes have simply extended the dangerous routes and streets to what used to be quiet streets for kids to walk along.
name: Lmiyake

comment: Again, thank you for bringing this issue to our attention.  After taking a closer look of the area, we have determined that the wall graffiti is too far into private property and the Midtown Green Team is not responsible for tackling issues on private property unless it is a matter of public safety.  However, we will pass this issue on to a City of Atlanta crew to see if they are able to resolve this issue.  We will keep you updated on any decisions made by the City.  Thank you for keeping Midtown safe and clean.

comment: Thank you for taking the time to report this issue.  Midtown Alliance is a non-profit organization working to improve the Midtown Community.   While basic infrastructure repair and maintenance remain the responsibility of the City of Atlanta, our full-time staff works to enhance these services in the district.  To this end, we address outstanding issues as quickly as we can and as our budget and authority allow.  For those issues that lie outside of our purview, we will advocate for resolution on your behalf.  The appropriate personnel at Lanier Parking has been notified and we will continue to keep you updated on this issue.
name: Brittney, Midtown Blue Staff

comment: The projects that you see happening at ponce between Piedmont and Spring are being funded by the Midtown Improvement District, not the city of Atlanta.  Unfortunately the block that you are referring to is well outside of our district so we are not able to spend funds there.  The City does have plans to improve Ponce--but I am not sure when these will take place.  I agree that Ponce is desperately in need of improvements along its length to Moreland.  The improvements in Midtown were done to calm traffic, improve the pedestrian environment, and two-way the street between Peachtree and Spring to improve traffic flow.  I hope this information was helpful.
name: Nathan, Midtown Alliance Staff
user: {u'public_filename': u'/files/user_images/0001/6527/M_Symbol_BusinessBlue.jpg', u'name': u'Nathan, Midtown Alliance Staff', u'witty_title': u'Heman', u'place_id': 75434, u'civic_points': 5310, u'id': 33226, u'reported_issue_count': 103, u'square_image': u'/files/user_images/0001/6527/M_Symbol_BusinessBlue_square.jpg', u'comments_count': 72, u'following_issue_count': 0, u'can_ack': True, u'voted_issue_count': 0, u'closed_issue_count': 53}

comment: That comment is a bit unfair--I gave  factual statements in response to your request for an explanation--not rhetoric.  I agree that Ponce needs more improvements further down the corridor--but the we are not allowed to spend MID funds outside of the MID district.  We hired transportation engineers to study the entire network of intersections in that area--14 in all--and devised a comprehensive plan to improve traffic flow in the area.  This project is the first part of that effort. We are also currently installing intelligent traffic signals that will be coordinated through a central monitoring location so they can be adjusted for special events (such as shows at the Fox), congestion, accidents, rush hour and so on.  The improvements to one intersection must be appreciated in the context of the whole.  I have hear that the Ponce streetscape to Moreland is moving forward so your concerns will be addressed.  I hope my response has answered some of your questions.
name: Nathan, Midtown Alliance Staff

comment: On a Saturday ride with Va-Hi Velo we headed south on Highland from Aurora Coffee. We have ridden this stretch many times. I thought we were going straight towards downtown and was in the right lane. The group decided to go left at the light. Being very aware of the expansion joint. I approached carefully. I went to hop the joint and misjudged the distance, landing in the joint where it was about an inch deep. I fell catching my full wieght on my wrist. It was dislocated and had multiple breaks. Hopefully the image will spur some action on getting this fixed. I go for surgery, plate and screws tomorrow.
name: Mike

comment: Over the years this expansion joint has injured many cyclist from pro racers in the Tour de Georgia to commuters indicating just how persistently dangerous this joint is.  We all know about it but it continues to injure us.   I remind my cycling friends about the expansion joint but we all come close to dropping our tires into it one day or another.  Riders will continue to be injured until it is fixed.
name: Tom Beisel

comment: Rebecca - did your site visit with Public Works take place? If so, what became of the conversation? This side path remains extremely dangerous.
name: cabbagetowner

comment:
Yes, we had a site visit over a year ago I believe. Not much to report - the path had been built, the road realigned with less space and not enough room for bike lanes. My goals were to 1) help the city engineer understand why a sidepath would be less useful for city cycling than a bike lane to prevent this from happening in the future and b) to get ramps installed for access from side streets. 

Results were mixed. No ramps have been installed to my knowledge - I was told this was due to ADA, and the need to make the path safe for wheelchair users, which demonstrates why a bicycle lane was preferable in this location. The crossing at Piedmont remains very dangerous, as is the highway access ramp crossing - they did agree to install an additional sign warning of the ramp there. 

I would recommend contacting your city council member and copying the commissioner of public works on the email if you would like to weigh in. We gathered extensive feedback from cyclists but the reality is that once construction has started the advocates are too late. 

We started a neighborhood bicycle liaison program to try to stay better abreast of projects that affect conditions for cycling. Volunteers can "adopt" their neighborhoods by signing up here: http://www.atlantabike.org/node/1871
name: Rebecca Serna / Executive Director

comment: As of the end of September, 2011, this issue still has not been fixed. Crosswalks in all other directions activate automatically, but the east/west signal on the south side of the intersection (directing bicycle and pedestrian traffic on the PATH) does not activate unless the button has been pushed. If bicycle or pedestrian traffic arrives after the east/west auto light has turned green, they must either proceed against the 'don't walk' signal, or wait an entire light cycle before receiving a walk signal. This is a heavily used commuter route and remains very dangerous and inconvenient.
name: cabbagetowner

comment:
This car was parked in the bike lane on Monday. About a minute after taking the picture, the car pulled up next to me and started honking. The driver (whose wife apparently saw me taking the photo) began aggressively questioning me, taking pictures of me, and threatening legal action, as well as insinuating the possibility of other, supposedly more physical consequences. "You have to bike past here every single day. Could be very dangerous."

To me, he seemed very concerned about the possibility of his presence being associated with this particular location. Given his New Jersey plates, he probably wasn't too worried about receiving a cheap parking ticket from the APD that he won't ever have to pay. I won't speculate as to exactly what he was so concerned about, but I will note that every single car I've seen parked in this location has been different, and has had an out-of-state license plate. Which seems very strange to me.

The driver followed me to Inman Park station, at which point I entered the MARTA station to avoid further confrontation.
name: Stephen Touset

comment:
I'm glad nothing worse happened to you - scary!  

I went by the other day and, on seeing two cars parked in the bike lane, asked the two guys standing outside the pizza shop if they were their cars.  One said, yes, but I'm the store owner and my son is the car and the other said yes, but I'm the delivery guy.  They both agreed to move their cars after a short discussion of why it was dangerous, but I didn't see either move before the light changed and I rode away.  

The city has agreed to install "tow zone" signs but I have not seen them yet.

comment:
There's a no parking sign immediately next to the spot in question, which can be seen in the photos.

Honestly, though, I wonder if the best solution is to repaint the area. I don't see why the bike lane has to cut to the curb right there, as opposed to being next to parallel parking like it is ten feet further down the road.

I just get concerned about this particular location, because it's right where the bike lane starts at a pretty busy intersection. Cyclists crossing the street who go into the bike lane are immediately forced right back into the traffic that's been eagerly awaiting the cyclist getting out from in front of them.

comment:
It does seem strange to use the emergency call-in number for this, I must say.

First, it's no emergency. Second, it's about 100 percent unlikely that a tow company will hook its gear up to a cop car.

Better solution: stop bike; walk into Thumb's Up; (very) nicely inform the cops that there are, like, 10 miles of on-street bike lanes in the city and they're using one of the busiest for parking; and last, would it be all that hard to do the right thing?
name: Barry

comment:
Does this still happen? I bike this route daily, and haven't seen problems (except for immediately at the Edgewood/Boulevard intersection, which is a separate ticket). It may be a time-of-day, thing, which is why I'm asking.

There are "No Parking" signs and other similar signage letting people know that cars aren't supposed to park there. Which is about the best I think can be done, outside of individuals calling in reports to the police.

I think a lot of people are concerned about using 911 to call for a tow truck as well. Is there a non-emergency number to call that can be published somewhere?
name: MidtownCommuter

I think this is mostly a weekend occurence...

But during the week it's happening very frequently throughout the day just down the street.  I had lunch at Thumbs Up Monday and as I was leaving at 1 pm there were two cars parked in the bike lane down the street at the Blvd intersection (where it's most common).

comment:
I've come to the conclusion that the plastic bollards as implemented are effectively useless. I pass by these virtually every weekday, and there is always at least one knocked down. Every day I replace them, and the next day more are down again.

I believe this highlights the exact reason the bollards were put there in the first place -- to protect cyclists in the bike lane from cars turning right through the lane.

These should be replaced with permanent fixtures which stand a chance at actually preventing what they attempt to.

comment:
Agreed that this is a problem. Bollards should be constructed of a material that will both withstand and discourage contact, likely metal or concrete. How about a Jersey barrier? Undoubtedly, motorists have learned that driving over the existing plastic bollards has no adverse effects on their vehicle. Scarce city resources are being used to constantly replace these.

Also, I should note, these are very useful in forcing [most] motorists to slow down and take a wide turn, which helps immensely for preventing cyclists in the bike lane from getting squashed. Fix the issue, but don't discard the concept.
name: Cabbagetowner

comment: I find motorists travelling eastwards on Edgewood turning right onto Krog are liable to cut me off with the dreaded "right hook" when I'm cycling straight through intersection between the bollards and curb.   A more effective strategy would be the "stop line" for cars to be painted further back (~10 feet) and a separate "stop line" for bikes be painted forwards so as to be visible to drivers.   Instead of the flimsy plastic tubes we should consider a concrete barrier.
name: A Murrill

comment: The location on the map is a little off- the problem is actually just west of Waddell on Edgewood (heading west). Deep holes, very dangerous at night. Also, they are just after a crosswalk with a yellow 'stop for pedestrians' sign in the middle of it, so if cars get a little close to cyclists in the bike lane right there (to avoid the sign), there is no way for cyclists to avoid the holes.

Potholes are still there and getting worse. Particularly the right side of the lane heading from Wylie to Dekalb, towards the light. This is where cyclists ride, it can be dark, and the holes are getting deeper.
name: lisa

comment: Another person wants this fixed too!
As of Aug 23, they are still not fixed (taken out). We rode by today and they are still there. This is an crash waiting to happen, if it has not already happened.
Another person wants this fixed too!

Acknowledged by ABC - we have mentioned this to the city several times and today were told they are going to remove the 2 feet on the right side of the bump to allow bikes to pass through.  They will also install a reflective strip in front of the bumps.  Ride by next week and let us know if it worked!

comment: That's great to hear!   Last night I had to dump out on the grass because of this hazard as a car came about an 1" of passing me because the vehicle driver had no where to go - and this hole was filled with rain water - yikes!!   I will keep you posted......thanks much.
name: Mike and Pam

comment: Approximately 2 feet of the bumps have been removed from the right side and the remaining surface looks like it has been milled a bit, similar to shallow rumblestrips, but seems fine for riding on. Not sure if there is more work to come. I think there is still an issue with the bumps if riders can't see the removed section in the dark, perhaps the above-mentioned reflective strips will solve this.
name: lisa

comment:
Picture. This still doesn't look safe. There is, as mentioned, 2 feet of bumps removed and milled. That specific section seems fine to ride on, but there's no indication that cyclists should ride only there.

There are some reflective strips, but nothing that would actually indicate that it's something unsuitable for cyclists to cross over.

comment:
I actually provided SEVERAL pictures and a cross street location. There is no address. There is an empty softball field right behind the aparments on Thomasville Boulevard. The grass is so high on the sidewalk that you have to walk in the street. It has been like this for years. The sidewalk is covered in weeds. Kids have to walk in the street to get home. There is a fire hydrant buried in there somewhere. 

There is a also a stop sign at the corner of Thomasville Boulevard and Fulton Bridge that is covered in weeds. You have to drive out partially into the street to see if a car is coming. I almost got hit by a police car one night.
name: Nicol

comment:
I have no idea how to use the goolge maps link attachment or whatever that thing on the side of my screen is. It wasn't even part of my original email to See Click Fix seven months ago. I was able to attach several pictures and now on this link I am only able to attach one.   The intersection is Thomasville Bouleard  and Fulton Bridge, S.E. Atlanta, 30315. Thomasville Boulevard is right of off McDonough Boulevard and McDonough Blvd is right of off Moreland Ave before you get to the Starlight Drive in. 

The weeds are growing into the street and beginning to crack the pavement. I went for a walk in 2009 and haven't been able to walk on the sidewalk since then. Someone owns this propery and they need to come take care of it. It is a serious safety hazzard. 

There is a big empty softball field that is overgrown with weeds. Several years ago there was a group that would come every month and play there and now nobody ever goes there and it is seriosly neglected. I have no idea what is going on.
name: Nicol

comment: I opened this issue 541 days ago. Bill Kennedy Way is a major thoroughfare for cyclists, providing one of the safest I-20 crossings along the southeast corridor (only the Cherokee St. crossing in Grant Park provides a safer passage, but it doesn't provide for northbound trips or access to the beltline as well as BKW). All it would take would be some light demolition, rebuilding a short section of sidewalk and curb, and repaving a patch of the street. Hardly a TSPLOST-sized project scope.

comment: Since I reported this issue 541 days ago, the road condition has gotten 541 days worse. The bridge expansion joints on Bill Kennedy Way where the street meets the bridge were erroneously paved over years ago. comment: It should also be noted that Atlanta's Fire Station #10 is located 1 mile north of this extremely bad crossing. comment:
Ms. Johnson,
Thank you for contacting the City of Atlanta - Department of Public Works. A service request has been created for a traffic study to install a crosswalk and pedestrian light at Campbellton road and Cascade Glen. Typically, a traffic study can take up to 30 days before a decision is made by the Office of Transportation to approve or decline the installation of a crosswalk. At that time, you may contact Customer Service at publicworks@atlantaga.gov  or 404-330-6333 to receive a status update. Your confirmation number for this request is 805942. Thank you!
name: Atlanta Public Works

comment: Thank you for your speedy response. However, in evaluating the situation, please do not overlook the concerns the driving leaving the complex are facing. It is equally important as the pedestrian issue.

comment: Good morning, I have a problem with our street sign.  It's been leaning for the last few months & will you please send someone from the city to straighten out or replace it please.  Really would appreciate it.  This is my second request on the matter.  Thanks, Stan.
name: Stanley C Horton

comment: Please fix this part of I-20. I am so tired of trying to dodge these "hugemongous " wholes and metal sticking out on this access bridge. People swerve to avoid this obstacle course. It is absolutely rediculous to think that the ciy of atlanta wants to build a brand new facolns stadium for a billion dollars and can't fix a road problem to keep their citizens out of harms way.
name: L

comment:
As of 11 Nov 2012, SOME of the seams appear to have been filled with a type of patch material. However, not all of them have been done. Plus, during this period, MORE joints along the Fulton Ind Blvd to I 85 interchange are coming loose. 
   Seems like more priority is given to the North end of the Interstate than the South end, IMHO.  The DOT seems to always fix their roads MUCH faster than over here.
name: Reggie

comment: Please fix immediately. You literally have to swerve in another lane to avoid busting you tire axels if you are not familiar with this part of the road.
name: L

comment:
It's now July 10, 2013, and it looks like they "patched" some of the seam on the eastbound side. But left other parts undone (esp. 2nd lane from right EB approx 1/2 mi east of I 285) , so you're still having to get jolted if you happen to be in the affected lane.
   As for the westbound side ( esp. 2nd lane form right), it appears nothing has been done. I guess the DOT is taking a "wait until someone has a blowout/accident" approach (on both sides), before they address the issue.
name: Reggie

comment: They're (DOT) seemingly concentrating on the NORTH side (e.g., Riverside Drive) area of I 285, while the south west end egt minimal repairs. The seams are still in need of repair.
name: Reggie

comment: This problem is on Armour Drive where the new paving was done.  Yes, it took 6 weeks to go from prep to paving, and yes, the contractor paved during rush hour on Monday morning.  That said, the bottleneck  that has resulted from the two lanes being marked as one is the worst issue of all.  For the past two days since it was done, it has taken between 30 - 45 minutes to go only one block and get through the intersection.  PLEASE help!  The yellow line, single lane marking is incorrect and impacted severely by all the traffic from the park and coming off exit 86 from the interstate.

comment: The sewer project on Roswell Road...I agree.  I live in the area and the neighborhood was assured by the city this would not happen, but here we are... smell and all.
name: Concerned citizen

comment: When the sewer tunnel was being constructed the residents of Interlochen Drive were assured by Clare Muller and Kay Norwood that there would be completely adequate filters on the sewer vent at Roswell Road and there would be no smell. Based on this we all got behind the project and helped promote support for it. Now the street truly stinks and it seems nothing is being done. Please fix this !!!!
name: Mac Ryland
user: {u'public_filename': u'', u'name': u'Mac Ryland', u'witty_title': u'Street Smart', u'place_id': None, u'civic_points': 60, u'id': 91421, u'reported_issue_count': 0, u'square_image': u'', u'comments_count': 1, u'following_issue_count': 0, u'can_ack': False, u'voted_issue_count': 0, u'closed_issue_count': 0}

comment:
S
Seriously, this needs to be corrected! I endured over a year of blasting for the construction of the sewer tunnel and now this! The smell is horrific and our backyard is our haven.  We pay over $1,200/year for sewer and water service. Please fix it.
name: 164 Interlochen

comment: I have lived here in Buckhead for twenty years and this is simply unprecedented. The smell is simply overwhelming at times. How can this possibly be allowed to continue? I am certain that if one of our city leaders arrived home each evening to the smell of disgusting sewer-ness......over and over and over again, that this problem would be solved. Mayor Reed, where is the leadership?
name: Chris Thornton
user: {u'public_filename': u'', u'name': u'Chris Thornton', u'witty_title': u'Street Smart', u'place_id': None, u'civic_points': 60, u'id': 91542, u'reported_issue_count': 0, u'square_image': u'', u'comments_count': 1, u'following_issue_count': 0, u'can_ack': False, u'voted_issue_count': 0, u'closed_issue_count': 0}

comment: I agree with all of the above comments.   On numerous occasions we have had to move inside because the smell was so horrid we couldn't enjoy our back yard.  Even having a fire in a fire pit doesn't mask the smell.  We supported the sewer project because we were assured that there would never be any odor from the sewer and now, with the stench occurring more often,  we all feel that we are getting no support from anyone in the city.  Please help.
name: Guest

comment: I reaffirm Mac Ryland's comments above.  II used to live on Interlochen Drive and now live at Rosewood Plantation Condos on Roswell.  I can even smell the stench in my home at times.  Besides being a quality of life issue, this is getting to be a known aspect of living in our area, and will most assuredly affect our property values as well.  I have also emailed Ms. Adrean twice about this problem.  Please fix this!
name: Barbara Smalley
user: {u'public_filename': u'', u'name': u'Barbara Smalley', u'witty_title': u'Street Smart', u'place_id': None, u'civic_points': 60, u'id': 91551, u'reported_issue_count': 0, u'square_image': u'', u'comments_count': 1, u'following_issue_count': 0, u'can_ack': False, u'voted_issue_count': 0, u'closed_issue_count': 0}

comment: Having several friends on Interlochen Drive, and because I live and shop nearby, this is a subject of great interest to me. The Chastain Square Publix is close to this stench pool, and Mirko Pasta Restaurant and Buttermilk Cafe are even closer to it.  Yesterday, (December 10) I turned from Lakemoore Drive onto Roswell Road heading to Mirko, and I thought something had gone terribly wrong INSIDE my car, even though the windows were raised.  This has to be a Georgia EPD issue if not a federal EPA issue.  In any case government attention to it should rise far above the City of Atlanta water department level.  If Mayor Franklin could resolve the Chattahoochee pollution crisis with the feds, surely Mayor Reed can nip this problem in the bud before it reaches state or federal fine level.
name: Frequent Gagger

comment: The smell is horrible and should not have to be endured.  Not only is it foul, it is embarrassing. I live on the corner of Roswell Rd and Interlochen and it is unbearable and totally unacceptable.  Our neighborhood deserves to have this issue addressed immediately.  Please move it to the top of the priority list.  I am personal friends with several of the local news reporters and plan to make a call to have this story covered if it is not addressed by the end of this week.
name: Over it!
